{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-04921/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-04921"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:49:21"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["close-up"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["eye-level"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["fixed"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman speaks pointedly to a man offscreen."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-04921","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-04921"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1/4862d32d-0ec2-43c0-878e-2b04ddf4e87d","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:31:19.441Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>When Cyril reminds Reynolds that “Barbara Rose pays for this house,” her words make clear a key theme of the film—the link between art and commerce. While Reynolds would rather have nothing to do with the financial side of his enterprise, which his sister maintains, and remain above it all in the realm of a pure aesthetics divorced from considerations of money, he nonetheless clearly benefits from the haute couture world in which he operates. Cyril's words underscore that Reynolds the artist cannot divorce himself from that equation. In this way, Reynolds is not unlike other artist figures in PTA’s filmography such as Jack Horner of <em>Boogie Nights</em> whose desire to maintain artistic integrity and vision bump up against commercial pressures and shifts in the marketplace. It’s easy to see a little bit of PTA with his idiosyncratic filmmaking in these figures.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:35.28988183161012,39.96353397341238,315.57191654357456,231.66774372230418"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1/0e1b3a58-16fe-4f14-b9bd-a3ee8c335095","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:31:51.307Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Cyril’s barbed phrase, “If you can stomach it,\" is well chosen, given that Alma will soon begin poisoning Reynolds. The film is very much about what one can “stomach” in a relationship and in a partner, what one will put up with for love, and what one desires from a partner.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04921/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:794.1663589364846,688.59721196455,379.36207533234847,281.6031203840472"}}}]}]}]}